        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The peak of the dust thermal emission depends, of course, on theequilibrium 
temperature. For the dust continuum we assume a temperature of 10K and 20K and 
model the SED with a modified blackbody. We normalize this SED via theFIR-SFR 
conversion from Kennicutt (1998) assuming an SFR of 40solar masses per year. For 
our target, due to the lensing, this corresponds to an intrinsic SFR of only 10 
solar masses per year. Using the sensitivity calculator we expect to reachthese 
limits (5 to 10 sigma per beam) in 2.8 hours on-source for band 6. The OT 
estimates a total time request of 5.5 hours including calibrations and overheads.

For the CO(6-5) line we use our fiducial (molecular) gas mass limit of10 billion 
solar masses to estimate the line flux. We further assume that the number density 
of CO relativeto H2 is 10^{-6} and estimate a peak flux density of . Using the 
sensitivity calculator for the lowest spectral resolution, we estimate to reach 
this fluxdensity limit (3-sigma) in one hour of exposure time. This 
estimatedepends strongly on the density and temperature of the gas. We 
haveassumed here that all of the CO is above the critical density for 
thistransition. In the case that the line is undetected we should still detect 
the dust continuum in that spectral window.  </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
