    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>In the gas-rich, high-redshift universe there are already exist massive quiescent 
galaxies. An unknown mechanism is able to stop and keep the gas from cooling and 
forming stars. Furthermore, these galaxies are on average much smaller than 
galaxies of a similar mass ($10^11 M_{\odot}$) in the present-day universe.It is 
clear that these galaxies must undergo further evolution. The degree to which 
they are quenched and the presence of residual gas are two key parameters which 
will govern their future evolution.

We propose here to make dust continuum and CO line observations of a lensed, 
massive post-starburst galaxy z=2.15. Our target has deep spectra fromVLT/X-
SHOOTER and shows strong Balmer absorption lines as well as dust extinction. The 
combination of the unrivaled sensitivity of ALMA and the lensing amplification 
will enable us to place the most stringent  constraints on the efficiency of 
quenching both in terms of residual star-formation and of leftover fuel for 
forming more stars. We will use these data to infer the possible mechanism(s) 
responsible for the cessation of star-formation. </prp:abstract>
